<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-s03e02" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Episode 2: Simplifying Fractions</title>
    <assemblage>
        <title>Episode 2 Learning Goals</title>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Simplify fractions
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </assemblage>
    <assemblage>
        <title>Episode 2 Key Terminology</title>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Equivalent
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Simplify
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </assemblage>
    <p>
        Notice that it's possible to have two fractions that look different, but they actually represent the same amount (they are equal).
    </p>
    <figure>
        <caption>Common fractions of inches on a tape measure.</caption>
        <image source="measuringtape.jpg" width="80%">>
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      For example, on a tape measure, we can see that 2/8 of an inch is the same as 1/4 of an inch. These fractions are equal.
      <md>
        \frac{2}{8} = \frac{1}{4}
      </md>  
    </p>
    <figure>
        <caption>Common fractions of inches on a tape measure.</caption>
        <image source="eqfractions.png" width="90%">>
        </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      From a picture, we can see that 1/2 of a pizza is the same amount as 2/4 of that pizza. It's also the same as 3/6 of that pizza, and it's also the same as 4/8 of that pizza. 
      All these fractions are equal.  
      <md>
        \frac{1}{2} = \frac{2}{4} = \frac{3}{6} = \frac{4}{8}
      </md>
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-equivalent">
        <statement>
            <p>
               Equal fractions are sometimes also called <term>equivalent</term>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
        <alert>Making Equivalent Fractions</alert>
    </p>
    <p>
        There are two actions that make a fraction look different but keep it equal to what it was originally:
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                Multiply the numerator and denominator by the same number.  
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                Divide the numerator and denominator by the same number (called “simplifying” because it makes the fraction simpler)
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
        For example, if I start with the fraction 1/2, and I multiply the numerator and denominator by 4:
        <md>
            \frac{1\times 4}{1\times 4} = \frac{4}{8}
        </md>
        I get 4/8, which we saw earlier is equal to 1/2.
    </p>
    <p>
        If I start with the fraction 3/6, and I divide the numerator and denominator by 3:
        <md>
            \frac{3\div 3}{6\div 3} = \frac{1}{2}
        </md>
        I get 1/2, which we saw earlier is equal to 3/6.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-simplify-fraction">
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Simplify</term> a fraction by dividing the numerator and denominator by the same number. If no whole numbers divide both the numerator and denominator,
                then the fraction is said to be <term>simplified</term> to <term>lowest terms</term>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
        <alert>How to Fully Simplify a Fraction</alert>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Find a number that divides both the numerator and denominator of the fraction.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Divide the numerator and denominator by this number. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Repeat steps 1-2 until there are no more numbers that divide both numerator and denominator.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <example>
        <p>
            Simplify the fraction
            <md>
                \frac{12}{18}
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Solution 1: I notice that the number 2 divides both 12 and 18.
            <md>
                \frac{12\div 2}{18\div 2} = \frac{6}{9}
            </md>
            I notice that the number 3 divides both 6 and 9:
            <md>
                \frac{6 \div 3}{9\div 3} = \frac{2}{3}
            </md>
            There are no numbers that divide both 2 and 3, so the fully simplified fraction is: <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Solution 2: I notice that the number 3 divides both 12 and 18.
            <md>
                \frac{12\div 3}{18\div 3} = \frac{4}{6}
            </md>
            I notice that the number 2 divides both 4 and 6:
            <md>
                \frac{4\div 2}{6\div 2} = \frac{2}{3}
            </md>
            There are no numbers that divide both 2 and 3, so the fully simplified fraction is: <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>
        </p>
    </example>
</section>